Harvard students take a course on how enough to rest
A new course at Harvard University this year provided all its students with more sleep. This is an attempt to fight the growing culture of cool learning all night after refueling caffeine.
The teacher found that the number one university students in the world are often uneducated when it comes to the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaseler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham Women's Hospital, developed a course that he believes is the first such course in the United States.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end, one girl approached him and said, “Why am I being told this now, in the last year?”
“She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep that surprised me,” a teacher from The Telegraph shared.
In the course, which was first introduced this year, students are explained by the basics of how good sleep habits help achieve academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s medical services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously deprived of sleep for a week.
The hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section has images of a room in a hostel where students click cups of coffee, curtains, simulators and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deficiency on sports performance, and the importance of sleep-related routine.
In another section, participants tell how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Next, the campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change students’ behavior instantly.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have the right to know about the effects of smoking cigarettes for health,” added Professor Chaisler.
The culture of pride for “sleeping all night” still exists, he added, and also noted that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
A sufficient sleep of good quality should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even with a gain of excess weight, since sleep deprivation translates the brain into a hunger regime that causes constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaseler develop a course after enrolling on one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to appeal to all graduate students with a request to undergo a similar program of study before coming to a competitive institution.
