The long-suffering frigate F125 got into newspaper headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into operation and returned it to the Blohm + Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the return of a warship to a shipbuilding company after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media mentioned significant "defects of software and equipment", due to which the combat vessel became unsuitable for military operations.
The disadvantages of software are particularly important, since the crew of the Baden-Wurtemberg-class ship consists of about 120 sailors - this is only half the number of military personnel who served on the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the vessel has a significant excess of weight, which worsens its performance and limits the possibilities for further modernization.
The Reinland-Pfaltz frigate is twice as heavy (7,000 tons) for ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty equipment, another problem was the total cost of the project, which also includes the price of crew training.
The expected 2.2 billion euros turned into a colossal 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion US dollars).
Problems with obtaining new frigates have gained special weight in light of recent warnings about the decline of the German naval forces.
