The National Trust will watch the secret life of bats
A new study, which is conducted in land ownership in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the data obtained will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in order to take measures to preserve them in the future.
In the Inveryu gardens in Wester-Rosss, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe species such as non-topir dwarfs and a non-topir pigmey, as well as ears ordinary and water night.
Special registrars will be placed in strategic locations on land ownership to observe bat behavior during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using hand detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to establish the frequency and belonging of bat screams.
Then it is planned to develop a detailed map of animal habitat and prepare a report to link animal behavior with their habitat.
Rob Dewar, an advisor on nature protection at the National Trust of Scotland, hopes the results of the study will help determine which areas of residence are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of habitat care measures (e.g., meadow formation) and identify optimal methods of preserving forests for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations have decreased significantly in Scotland and in the UK.
They are threatened with active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of nesting sites.
Among other negative factors are wind installations and lighting, adhesive paper for flies, chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks of domestic cats.
The bats are not blind.
However, due to hunting at night, the ears are more effective to help them catch prey than their eyes.
They use a complex echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles to flight trajectories.
In the National Trust of Scotland, which takes care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of special importance and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, take bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct research, inspection nesting sites and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland. It is located on the territory of the Trive in the Dumfris and Galloway region. It found refuge eight of the ten types of bats living in Scotland.
David Thompson argues that this is the perfect place for them.
“There are excellent conditions for bats on the territory of the city,” he assures.
“There are old buildings, many huge trees and other favorable living conditions.
However, we still need to learn a lot about bats. Thanks to the research we do here and elsewhere, we will be able to learn more about what they need for prosperity."
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for bats before any technical work, since due to the unintentional destruction of one nesting site for the removal of young people, up to 400 females with cubs can die, which is likely to cause the destruction of the entire local population.
The bats and their nests are protected by law. The animal is forbidden to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Center, urged the public to join the organization's efforts.
She said, "We still need to learn a lot about our bats. We have not yet revealed the characteristic features of populations of many species."
