The largest situation escalated this week due to new tariffs on goods worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), which actually taxes half of all goods that come to the United States from China.
Beijing paid off the same coin every time, recently imposing a duty of five to ten percent on U.S. goods worth $60 billion.
China has pledged to take similar US measures, and the world’s second largest economy is unlikely to miss the opportunity to keep that promise in the near future.
To force Washington to retreat is to agree with the demands, but for Chinese President Xi Jinping, the public worship of the United States is too shameful.
However, as experts believe, if Beijing takes advantage of the situation correctly, pressure in the trade war with the United States could bring China an advantage in the long term, reducing the relationship between the two economies.
“A quick political solution in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that will lead to a sharp economic fall in any country. And that actually poses a greater threat than observers have previously recognized,” said analyst Abigail Grace, who deals with Asia-related issues at the Center for New American Security think tank.
Foreign Minister says Syria 'ready' to return refugees
Syria says it is ready to voluntarily return refugees and seek help in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that lasted more than seven years.
Speaking to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Mualem said conditions in the country were improving.
“Today, the real situation has become more stable and safer thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to restore the areas destroyed by terrorists so that people can return to normal life.
All conditions have been created for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave through terrorism, as well as unilateral economic measures that influenced their daily lives and limited their livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Mualem said the Syrian government would be pleased to accept assistance in restoring the war-torn country.
But he stressed that they would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from countries that support the riot.
